< Rating>
4</Rating>
< text>
This probably as good a place to find coffee as you're going to find in the North Bay. It's in the Barlow Center, just down the street from the Rialto Cinema and, beyond that, Whole Foods. There is parking but I'm noticing it is not as plentiful as it was, even not that long ago. WiFi is available and decent. It has baked goodies but few are vegan. Also, if you want a pour-over (my own preference), try to get your order in before 2 pm.<//text>

One of the best places to get Coffee in Sonoma County.

Even though Taylor Maid Farms was recently purchased, this coffee bar brews some of the most consistently good coffee here in Sonoma County.

If you're interested in fine coffees brewed well, you can do a lot worse than here.</review>

< Text>
I haven‚Äôt yet picked up my dry cleaning or tailoring and cannot yet speak to quality, but be sure to ask about pricing when you go. There are no price lists posted in the store or online and my dry cleaning pickup receipt did not have a total on it. When I asked how much it would be the clerk told me I had to wait while she ‚Äúentered it in.‚Äù While I waited another woman came in to drop off and said ‚Äúhow much will it be? You guys are really shady about pricing.‚Äù And was told to wait to find out, the same as me. Whatever system is currently in use is not transparent to the customer, I‚Äôve never experienced this at any other dry cleaner.

The price for dry cleaning was not exorbitant, however my pants thats are having alterations done are shockingly expensive. <resp>None</resp><UserId.>108409426564624430185< /UserId.>< Review>
This church is beyond organized. But on top of that, they are clearly in the business of loving God and sharing that love with others.

My husband and I started attending last November with our twin boys. Right from the beginning, we loved what was going on in the kids' ministry. We LOVED the Celebrate Recovery ministry (and we are now involved in it!) We loved that the worship is not about putting on a "show". It is a deep, meaningful outpour of collective praise to God. It's real stuff. You can feel the presence of God. Then the pastor. Lord have mercy. The messages are so on point - not too long, but long enough that I feel I was just fed a great spiritual meal. Topics that are super relevant, and things I need to be ministered to about. So there's an intro that's like a story. Then there's meat and potatoes - solid biblical verses, historical input, and contextual insight so we UNDERSTAND what's happening and what God is doing in that moment in the Bible. Then, the close - HOW THIS RELATES TO ME and what I should do about it from GOD's words, not anyone else's. I honestly am so grateful that we came to Rocky Peak. There are places you just go to. And then, there are places that God leads you to. There is a difference. Go check it out.</Review>

<rating>5</rating>< Text>
We've been going to Rocky Peak Church now for over a month and in this short period of time, we have absolutely fallen in love with this church.  From the teaching, to the worship, to the community of people who are loving and non judgmental, to the donuts and coffee out front (which by the way, you can bring inside), we love it!  We are growing here and will be raising our family at Rocky Peak!

It's also worth mentioning that my wife and I have been to many other churches in the SFV over the years (consistantly) and even came to Rocky Peak once in the past (I think we were looking for something smaller at the time), but we now have found what we were looking for here at Rocky Peak!  God knew what we needed at the right time (It was worth not giving up!).</Text>

<review>I have been a Banfield wellness plan customer for 8 years, and recently moved to the area. I took my dog in for a semi-emergency for a wound cleaning and evaluation. This happened again when I went to pick up my dog - I paid and then waited, and waited, before the person who checked me out went and got my dog. I understand that they are busy, but this seemed to be an indicator that they easily miss things and set the visit off on the wrong foot.
In addition, the doctor who called was not very responsive to the symptoms and description of the issue and seemed to push an agenda in terms of what they thought was wrong. They charged me for a wound cleaning, bandage, and sent us home with antibiotics and said to come back in 10 days. No one called to follow up on us, which is normal practice for Banfield hospitals that we've visited in the past.
All of this added up to an uneasy feeling for me, so I ended up getting a second opinion at another local vet, who diagnosed my dog with a semi-rare infection that requires a lot more care than we ever would've gotten from Banfield.
As a result of this experience, I have cancelled my wellness plan and moved my dog's care to the other vet - and I won't recommend the Banfield plans to anyone anymore. 111236235651922060970<//userid>
< Text>
The only thing keeping this from a 1-star is the price. $11 is cheap! I did not go in knowing the price, but it all made sense when it came time to pay the bill: You get what you pay for. The location isn't easy to find and it is cash only, which makes things difficult.

The real issue is the cuts. If you plan to ask for anything more than "a number X on the sides and a Y on top" go somewhere else. I have a strong suspicion the word "fade" is not something this shop is familiar with. I will have to go somewhere else today to get my cut fixed.

For my young son, his cut was passable, but not anywhere near what I asked for.< /Text>

<pics>None<//pics>< Review>
I thoroughly enjoyed the Santa Paula Theater Center's production of Second Samuel, a poignant comedy they staged this summer (2013).  I don't like to read too much about a play before seeing one, preferring to experience it as the playwright's conversation with me, and so I took my seat with no expectations.  From the opening scene, I instantly fell in love with this production and stayed in love with it from start to finish.  The costumes and sets took me to a small town in Georgia that I still revisit in my mind.  The brilliant writing, acting and direction left me with questions I still ponder.  What makes any of us "too different" from the rest?  And what differences do our differences make?  Bravo to SPTC!  I'll be back to be entertained and enlightened by you again.< /Review>

I had to go back on three different occasions after my initial exam because I was given glasses with the wrong prescription, then another time the wrong measurements, another time because one pair wasn‚Äôt ready, and the frames for both glasses I purchased were flimsy and cheap not like the first time I bought here. The staff was nice but the service provided was not professional.

<GmapID>0x80d94e818da3aad1:0x649ba68d0751766</GmapID><user_id>106753237143716190781< /user_id><rating>3<//rating>< Time>
1595541784707</Time>
<review>They have a $59.95 promotion where you can get 2 glasses and an eye exam. It's a pretty good deal but watch out for the limited stock of these promotional glasses and the upsales!  There are only a  limited amount of these promotional glasses, like 20 pairs per section (men's, women's, etc). All the other glasses are priced higher and you get to pay for the more expensive of the 2 that you decide to get.  Then, if you want thinner lenses, bifocals, progressive, tinting or any extra niceties, it'll cost you more, sometimes a lot more. In addition, there were only 3 employees there and they were always juggling customers.

The day I went in, there wasn't an optometrist on the premises (Only on Mondays, apparently) so my eye exam was conducted remotely by a person on a computer monitor. She did a good job and produced a prescription for me. However, it was just for glasses and they needed to contact the doctor to get an updated prescription for contacts. That took an hour so I asked them what the holdup was and they said that they have to get an approval from the remote doctor but they didn't send the contact prescription so the technician has me redo the test again. <Text>UPDATED REVIEW 12/11/2018 - - -
Okaaay, I came back because of a Groupon that caught my attention. It was $150 for $32. I thought, "hey, now I can get a third awesome pair of glasses!"-- I knew I was going to be paying a little more than expected but.. dang, I almost regretted getting the Groupon at all. Quite the different experience than when I visited and reviewed back in April..

Upon arriving, they had no idea I was coming although I had called ahead and made an appointment. I initially spoke to Ivan who didn't know my name or why I was there. Quite the bummer since I explained everything over the phone. He informed me that I had called 'support line' instead of the actual store. Nevertheless, he was very willing to help me.

As much as he could, at least..

I explained to him I wanted the exact same type of glasses I had ordered back in April and was hoping to get them for the L O W L O W since I had the $150 Groupon. That's when he informed me he would try to "help me out" because he wouldn't be able to use that coupon with the pricing I received before. Maaaaaan.. I didn't get upset but it did make me roll my eyes and it let me know I had walked into a "used car dealership" kind of vibe. Huge bummer and very 'scam-esque'..

As much as Ivan wanted to help, there was still a tug-of-war between him and I. Where he wanted to try to get every single penny he could out of me and I wanted to save every single penny I could. I mean, I walked in there with a Groupon after all~.. I'm clearly trying to save some cash, man!

I wasn't rolling over for him and he (said he) couldn't provide me with the price I was looking for. I had walked in there thinking, "I'll pay $30 for my frames via Amazon, $32 for the Groupon and pay another.. what?.. $30 bucks at Stanton? Heck, let's make it $40 bucks! I'll get another pair for a total of ~$100 for a new pair altogether." -- that was not the case AT ALL. Ivan tried to get me to pay something like.. $170 for BETTER glasses (Ivan, if you're reading this, sorry if I forgot the exact amount, but it was ridiculous, man!). I cleaaarly wasn't having that. He then said something like $130? and that was totally not flying for me.

We WERE NOT on the same page..
Ivan had clearly had enough. I had communicated with him that it really felt like he was on commission and didn't want to go through all struggle. I wanted (again) the L O W L O W . I didn't want him asking him, "what's the most you want to spend today?". Like.. come on, man. Want me to say ten bucks? After some miscommunication, Ivan was visibly frustrated (and I get it.. I was NOT about to pay $100 bucks and he wasn't budging).

He said the magic word: Manager.

Nick came in to save the day.
He was much more understanding and had more power to get me a much more reasonable price. He got me the same pair of glasses I got earlier this year for $55 dollars. I was happy with that. Win some, Lose some.

Unfortunately, after this experience, I wouldn't recommend this store to EVERYONE. If you do decide you're brave enough, make sure you're ready to bargain and fight a little bit, like at the swap meet. Or if you have sales experience, that helps too!

I don't wanna give Nick anything lower than 3 stars after he hooked me up.

- - -

04/2018

I'd recommend it.

The price did drag me in, 2 for $69 is pretty awesome.. however, I knew my eyes were pretty bad. I figured the price would get bumped up one way or another.

It was.
I paid $49 for the exam and then was approached with a proposal of $359 for two AMAZING pair of glasses.
But.. there was the price jump.
From $69 to $400. Yikes.

Heather was extremely patient and helpful. We were able to go down to $110 for some lesser quality lenses. That plus the $49 eye exam. She threw in a few things too.
This didn't seem so bad. My eyes are horrible and require some thick lenses. I gotta be fair!
Ended up paying about $75 a pair.

4/5 stars becaaaause..
Although you can't call them a "SCAM".. you can say they have the intention of luring you in and then trying to upsell you.< /Text>< response>

< Review>
It was recently my very great pleasure to work with Michael on a mortgage for my new home.  I cannot praise him highly enough.  From my initial contact with him until the close of escrow, Michael worked tirelessly to find me the right mortgage and finalize every aspect of it.

Michael is very knowledgeable about the types of mortgage available and explained every option to me in very detailed emails and conversations.  He fully answered every question I had and usually anticipated my next question. In addition, he gladly responded to my numerous requests for "what it would look like" in different mortgage scenarios, based on varying down payments, house prices, etc.

Communication is the key to any undertaking involving more than one person, and Michael is one of the best communicators I have ever worked with.  His responses to my emails were lightning quick.  His explanations were very clear, easy to understand, and thorough. He kept me updated at all times about how the process was moving along, and he was able to meet my need for a three-week escrow closing.

Additionally, Michael's cheerful, upbeat personality and positive attitude made the entire transaction relatively pain free.  It was truly a delight working with Michael on my mortgage needs, and one could not go wrong in using his services.</Review>

<Time>1613842890328<//Time><rating>5< /rating><review>Park with playgrounds, hiking trails for all levels, and horseback riding. You can park inside (paid) or try to find street parking along the neighboring areas. It‚Äôs located right across the Puente Hills Mall, so you can easily grab a meal or go shipping before/after being at the park. Public restrooms are available and still open during covid. Masks are required.

There are a lot of different trails you can take and there‚Äôs workout equipment like pull up bars available. Some of the hikes do get a bit steep, but there are family-friendly options. There‚Äôs also a cement path for those looking for a more flat surface. There‚Äôs not a lot of shade, so bring a hat and wear sunscreen. There are a lot of picnic tables and I noticed a lot of families/groups using them. There are snakes and mountain lions so be mindful. Overall, this park provides a great way to have access to nature even in the middle of the ‚Äòburbs.<//review><pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNu342XBllvDWWOm7e9ACwNI2bj83RFoRLywf0f=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM5tZwc161aQZTatN19g9LeqI-Qu9Dgfh27R6oq=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMIfupl_karQcN5siSndQGktqFY4q1r96r5w9h9=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /pictures><resp>None< /resp><Gmap_id>0x80c2d586498d736f:0xeb32b2dcb72b5b6d<//Gmap_id></record></dataset><record>

<user_id>111212127579957762328< /user_id><Name>regis kwong</Name><Time>1611795046750</Time><Rating>5</Rating><Text>With the stay at home locked down ended yesterday, it‚Äôs the best time to go to parks to enjoy nature and soak up those much needed vitamin D to boost your immune system.

After the rain, the sky was extra blue and the air was so clear and fresh. Coming out to Schabarum regional park was the best decision. My wife and I heard that the stay at home locked down order had ended, we immediate decided to come to this park to catch the plum blossom before it‚Äôs too late.

This park is the only few of the parks in LA that have cheery and plum trees where they will blossom at the beginning of Spring. Without being able to go to Japan this year to view the Cherry blossom, this place is the closest thing.

It‚Äôs kind of interesting to know that in 1992, this park formed a sister relationship with Kairaku-En Park in Japan.

With the rain this week, the flowers are blossoming  with extra beauty. The colors of the flowers, white, red and pink blanketed the whole park. This scenery made you feel like you‚Äôre in Japan.

After gluttonous picture taking activities, we decided to hike up the hills to get some exercises. Once we get to the top, we were awed by the beautiful scenery of. The San Gabriel Valley. With the clear blue sky we can see all the way to the snowy top of Angeles Crest.

There are more to do in this park then just viewing cherry and plum blossoms. People come here to play soccer and tennis, picnic, hike, and horse back riding.

For the hikers, the trail here connects to the historic Juan Bautista De Anza National Historic Trail. There are plenty of parkings. Normally the fees for parking is $6. But during the pandemic, it seems that the parking is free. No body is at the gate to collect the fees.<//Text><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNCqxG_WjegYbC5S1uGewdbOnHyRvgiduAB08xn=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': <userid>106857796722466327941< /userid><Text>The Schabarum Skyline trail is truly one of a kind if you're looking for a variety of landscape for a jog, hike, or simply a walk. You can choose from a flat pavement to a more intense incline trail at a higher elevation. One thing I would note is this place have snakes and mountain lions which is typical in a vastness of grassland that considers to be a wilderness. It is advised to accompany with others if you decide to go on a wild hike. Also, there are horses that you can rent at the park if you want to have a wild experience.</Text><GmapID>0x80c2d586498d736f:0xeb32b2dcb72b5b6d</GmapID>< username>

<date>1616393454276</date><Review>The best local park to see cherry blossoms üå∏ Some are mature trees and some are newly planted
All cherry blossoms trees are donations from dr. Gu at Azusa in remembrance of their son who died in a hiking trip. They chose to turn grief into passion, the love of nature in a form of cherry blossoms which are enjoyed by so many people! While we are mesmerizing with its beauty, we always remember the pain that they went through. The pain of loosing a son who just graduated from university. <Text>This place is amazing it has plenty of space for picnics. It has plenty of space for family or friends get together. It has beautiful hiking trails and if you want to know one of them leads to horses. Some of the restrooms are open so you need to pay attention to the sign in the entrance to see which ones are. People take their bikes here so if you want bring yours. If you want a park that has tranquility this is definitely the one for you! My boyfriend and I make this our twice a month adventure.<//Text><name>Giovanna Flammia<//name>< gmap_id>

<name>Leslie Fregoso<//name>< review>
I head down at least once a week for my hike. Its lovely seeing the changing seasons throughout the year. From the park, you're able to see the changing foliage and cherry blossoms, and out on the trails, wildflowers bloom and give way to brush and the like. It's always a treat catching sight of all the wildlife on your way up as well. The trails aren't too daunting, and the park is large and lovely. Would highly recommend visiting with the whole family.</review>

<userid>116406692606685455509<//userid>< name>
Luciano Cuadra<//name>
< Date>
1563288747192</Date>
<rate>5<//rate>< text>
One of my favorite places in the San Gabriel Valley. Schabarum Park is the best way to "get out there" without really leaving suburban LA. There are miles of trails teeming with wildlife to be explored on foot, bike or horseback. Some trails are easy and popular with somebody always within eyesight. Others are more remote and it's easy to forget you're a few miles away from a mall. They do charge for parking on the weekends, so park across the street in the mall lot and walk over.< /text>

< userid>
108744880967016551049< /userid>
<username>Alastair Aitken</username>< date>
1615858240343<//date>
<rate>5<//rate>< Review>
The park itself if beautiful, and also allows access to miles of wilderness trails into the hills.  The trails allow walking, running, biking, and horseback riding.  Trails are closed for two days after rains.  Passing signs that indicate the trails are closed can result in a citation with a fine.  The trails are beautiful all year long and provide many views of wildlife and the cities below.<//Review>

< review>
Great trails up the hills with interesting climbs, for easy walking, mountain cycling and outdoor family fun. You will get a good exercise on this trail with great views.

Then come down and enjoy the greenery of the park if you want to do easy scooting rides, pushing baby prams with wide spacing to ensure everyone gets the exercising without crowding. Family enjoyed our outing here.<//review>

< text>
We were here to see the cherry blossoms.  There aren't lots of trees but good enough to take some pretty pictures.  Weekdays are less people with no parking fee charged.  When you enter to the front entrance, you'll keep driving down until you see the horse ranch on the left.  That's where all the pretty cherry blossoms are.</text>

< Review>
This is a huge park. There are trails, abundance of picnic tables with grills, parking spots, public restrooms and grassy areas to choose from. Great for walking, jogging and biking. The signs say no drones and skateboards are allowed. This was a great spot to walk our dog, she sure loved it. Watch out for snakes and mountain lions in the hills/trails. Make sure to check out their dedicated butterfly and humming bird area sanctuary next to the amphitheater.<//Review>

Beautiful park, and I've only seen 1% of it! It gets pretty busy so if you do come via car plan on being patient when parking as cars enter and exit. When I was there working on one of the several picnic tables I heard several car horns.

Four stars because the bathrooms were very gross and this was at 9 in the morning so you could tell they don't clean them overnight. Also picnic tables were very dirty and sticky. It wasn't from the trees, it was from beverages being spilled and other sorts that made it sticky.< /Review>

<user>111158142056966751770</user><user_name>Tiffany Duong<//user_name>< date>
1520316522812</date>
< Rating>
5< /Rating>
< text>
This is so much more than a park! Came here for a hike with a friend I hadn't seen in far too long, and we just explored and wandered around -- finding trails on hillsides that looked totally removed from the city, the horse stables, the tennis courts, and lots of lovely paved roads too. This park is the perfect spot for family fun days outside, picnics, engagement pictures, etc. It's right across the street from Puente Hills Mall, so if you don't want to pay for parking on the weekends or can't find a spot, head to the mall and walk across the street.

There's a few playgrounds and tons of clean bathrooms. Many groups use the park for weekend salsa, yoga, soccer lessons, etc. Wonderful community space and a great outdoors area for the inland empire.<//text>

<review>Schabarum Regional Park is one of those hidden gems in the larger LA area.  Despite being right next to one of the busiest freeways in the city, this is one of the cleanest and quietest parks I have ever been to.  It has great hiking trails and plenty of picnic areas.

I happen to go on a Sunday for a light picnic.  The weather was great for a picnic as the trees would alleviate from the heat, yet there were no picnic-ers.  Perhaps it had something to do with the $6 parking fee.  I thought this to be a small fee to pay for having a quiet picnic.  Sometimes you do want a large space just to yourself.< /review>< Pics>

102103962967456590224</UserId.>
<username>Lizeth Allman<//username>< Date>
1564836722353< /Date>
<rate>5<//rate>< Review>
Lots of parking throughout the park. Bathrooms ok the few times I've gone in. Great trails and beautiful views. Some family tried to close off the bridge leading to the jungle gym area one Satyrday because they reserved the tables for a party. A park worker found out or was informed of this and quickly came over to tell them they can't block access, and that they only have reservations to the tables and not the whole area, which is used by other families and children and pokemon players.
The grounds are nice, I have yet to step on any dog poop which is a huge plus. Dog walkers are considerate and restrain their pets and clean up after them. Just overall a really nice place for a hike, dog walking, picnics, and public events like the pet adoptions, music shows, and pokemon community days<//Review>

< Text>
A place where people of all ages and ethnic groups can be found using the wide public spaces available in this park. Numerous hiking trails of varying difficulty, as well as play areas for kids as well. You can call the city to reserve picnic tables, as well as other spaces for private events. Overall, a great public recreation area that meets the needs of the local community. Check it out for yourself. Park on side streets for free parking too</Text>

<name>Michael W< /name><time>1540690810620< /time><Rating>5</Rating><text>Trail length: 8/10      Trail difficulty: 4 - 6/10

Big park; restrooms near the parking area. Expect to pay a parking fee on the weekend, which helps maintain the park.  Plenty of shade near the parking and restrooms.

The trails can range from moderate to fairly difficult depending on which ones you take. Their are horse trails you can follow and some get really steep. Others are longer and meander along at a much gentler slope. Some of the trails have some shade but be prepared with a hat.

This places get fairly busy in all areas, from the park grass to any of the back trails, so expect to see people.<//text><Pics>None< /Pics>< response>
